<ArticleLayout
  title="Garage Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy"
  description="Before buying garage storage, check your available space, wall type, access, moisture, weight limits and what actually needs to be stored."
  category="Garage"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/garage.webp"
  imageAlt="An organised garage with wall storage, shelves and clear floor space"
>
  <p>
    Garage storage can look simple until shelves block the car door, tubs trap moisture,
    hooks are fixed into the wrong surface, or heavy items end up stored where they are
    awkward to lift down.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying more shelving, tubs, hooks, cabinets or wall systems, it is worth checking
    how the garage is actually used. Many Australian garages are not just for cars. They
    often hold tools, sports gear, camping gear, cleaning products, garden supplies, spare
    household items, bikes, pet gear, seasonal decorations and the things that do not seem
    to fit anywhere else.
  </p>
  <p>
    The problem is that garage storage can become unsafe, impractical or wasteful if it is
    bought before the space is measured properly.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide walks through what to check before buying garage storage, so you can choose
    storage that suits the space, the items being stored and the way the garage is used.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what the garage actually needs to do</h2>
  <p>
    Before measuring shelves or buying containers, decide what the garage needs to handle.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some garages need to keep one or two cars accessible. Others are used as a workshop,
    storage room, laundry overflow, home gym, bike area, garden shed substitute or general
    household dumping zone.
  </p>
  <p>The right storage depends on the main job of the garage.</p>
  <p>Common garage uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>parking one or more vehicles</li>
    <li>storing tools and hardware</li>
    <li>storing bikes, scooters or sports gear</li>
    <li>holding bulk household supplies</li>
    <li>storing garden tools and outdoor equipment</li>
    <li>keeping camping, beach or travel gear</li>
    <li>storing seasonal decorations</li>
    <li>holding cleaning products or chemicals</li>
    <li>creating a small workbench area</li>
    <li>keeping spare household items out of living spaces</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A garage used every day needs different storage from a garage that is mainly used for
    long-term overflow. Items used weekly should be easy to reach. Items used once or twice
    a year can usually be stored higher, deeper or further from the door.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort before buying more storage</h2>
  <p>
    Garage clutter often feels like a storage problem, but it is usually a sorting problem
    first.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you buy shelves before sorting the contents, you may simply create more places to
    keep things that should have been removed, recycled, donated or relocated.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, group items into simple categories:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Category</th>
        <th>Examples</th>
        <th>Storage implication</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Frequently used</td>
        <td>tools, bike helmets, cleaning supplies, pet leads</td>
        <td>needs easy access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Occasionally used</td>
        <td>camping gear, sports gear, car cleaning items</td>
        <td>can sit on shelves or in labelled tubs</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Seasonal</td>
        <td>Christmas decorations, beach gear, winter gear</td>
        <td>can be stored higher or further back</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Heavy</td>
        <td>paint tins, tools, hardware, bulk supplies</td>
        <td>should usually stay low</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Awkward</td>
        <td>ladders, long tools, bikes, folded chairs</td>
        <td>may need wall, vertical or dedicated storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hazardous or sensitive</td>
        <td>chemicals, batteries, fuels, sharp tools</td>
        <td>needs extra caution and restricted access</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    This sorting step helps you avoid buying the wrong type of storage. It also shows
    whether you need shelves, tubs, hooks, cabinets, pegboards, a workbench, wall rails or
    simply fewer items.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the usable floor space</h2>
  <p>
    Start with the floor, not the wall.
  </p>
  <p>
    A garage can look large when empty, but the usable storage space may be much smaller
    once you allow for the car, doors, walking paths and access to appliances or switches.
  </p>
  <p>Measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>total garage width</li>
    <li>total garage depth</li>
    <li>vehicle parking area</li>
    <li>space beside the vehicle with doors open</li>
    <li>walking space from the garage door to the house entry</li>
    <li>space around laundry appliances, if they are in the garage</li>
    <li>clearance around garage roller doors, tilt doors or sectional doors</li>
    <li>access to power points, switches, taps, meters or fuse boxes</li>
    <li>any steps, slopes, drains, posts or uneven sections</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not measure only the empty wall. Measure the space as it is used.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, a shelving unit may technically fit along the side wall, but still stop the
    car door opening properly. A deep cabinet may fit at the back of the garage, but make it
    difficult to walk around the car or reach the internal door.
  </p>

  <h2>Check vehicle clearance before choosing storage depth</h2>
  <p>
    If the garage still needs to fit a car, storage depth matters.
  </p>
  <p>
    Deep shelving and large tubs can quickly turn a two-car garage into a one-car garage, or
    make it difficult to open vehicle doors. This is especially common in narrow suburban
    garages, townhouses and older homes where garage dimensions are tight.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage for a side wall, park the car in its normal position and check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how far the car door opens</li>
    <li>whether passengers need to get in and out on that side</li>
    <li>whether mirrors, handles or charging cables need space</li>
    <li>whether children, pets or prams need to move through the area</li>
    <li>whether storage would make it harder to carry groceries or bags inside</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shallow shelf, wall rail or narrow cabinet may work better than a deep freestanding
    shelving unit if the garage is still used for parking.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure height, but do not assume higher is better</h2>
  <p>
    Garage walls often have useful height, but high storage is not always practical.
  </p>
  <p>Before planning tall shelves or high wall storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>ceiling height</li>
    <li>garage door track height</li>
    <li>roller door clearance</li>
    <li>lighting position</li>
    <li>power point and switch locations</li>
    <li>ceiling beams, exposed pipes or obstructions</li>
    <li>whether tall items will be stable</li>
    <li>whether stored items can be reached safely</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    High storage is generally better for lighter, rarely used items. Heavy items should
    usually stay lower, where they are easier to lift and less likely to cause injury if
    dropped.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid creating storage that requires unsafe reaching, climbing or lifting. If something
    needs to be accessed often, it should not be stored where it requires balancing on a step
    ladder every time.
  </p>

  <h2>Check wall type before considering hooks, rails or panels</h2>
  <p>
    Wall-mounted garage storage can be useful, but it should not be treated as a simple
    cosmetic choice.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying wall hooks, rails, pegboards, panels or hanging systems, check what type
    of wall you have and what the product requires.
  </p>
  <p>Garage walls may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>plasterboard</li>
    <li>brick</li>
    <li>concrete block</li>
    <li>timber-framed</li>
    <li>steel-framed</li>
    <li>lined or partially lined</li>
    <li>shared walls in a townhouse or unit</li>
    <li>walls with pipes, wiring or other services behind them</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume all wall storage can be attached safely to any wall.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the product's installation instructions, load rating and fixing requirements
    before buying. For heavy or awkward items, consider whether qualified installation is
    needed. Renters should also check lease conditions and get approval before drilling or
    permanently fixing storage to walls.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with ceiling and overhead storage</h2>
  <p>
    Overhead garage storage can look efficient, but it needs much more caution than basic
    tubs or freestanding shelves.
  </p>
  <p>Before considering ceiling-mounted storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the ceiling structure is suitable</li>
    <li>what the manufacturer requires</li>
    <li>maximum load ratings</li>
    <li>garage door clearance</li>
    <li>vehicle clearance</li>
    <li>access height</li>
    <li>how items will be lifted safely</li>
    <li>whether installation should be handled by a qualified person</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not use overhead storage for heavy items that are difficult to lift. Avoid storing
    anything overhead that could create a serious hazard if it falls.
  </p>
  <p>
    For many households, freestanding shelves or low wall storage may be a simpler,
    lower-risk option than ceiling storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Check shelf load ratings and item weight</h2>
  <p>
    Garage storage often holds heavier items than indoor storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Shelves may need to hold paint tins, tools, hardware, car products, camping equipment,
    boxes of household goods or bulk supplies. These can become heavy quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying shelving, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>maximum total load</li>
    <li>maximum load per shelf</li>
    <li>whether the unit needs to be fixed to a wall</li>
    <li>whether the feet need a level floor</li>
    <li>whether the shelves suit moisture or dust</li>
    <li>whether the shelves can handle unevenly shaped items</li>
    <li>whether the shelf depth suits your tubs or boxes</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not rely on appearance alone. A shelf that looks sturdy may still have a low load
    rating. Also check whether the load rating assumes even weight distribution.
  </p>
  <p>
    Heavy items should usually be kept on lower shelves. Frequently used items should be
    between knee and shoulder height where possible.
  </p>

  <h2>Check moisture, dust and pests</h2>
  <p>
    Garages are often less sealed than indoor rooms. Some are dry and clean. Others are
    dusty, damp, hot, humid or exposed to pests.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether your garage has:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>water entering under the door</li>
    <li>damp corners</li>
    <li>condensation</li>
    <li>mould-prone areas</li>
    <li>gaps where pests enter</li>
    <li>dust from the road, driveway or workshop use</li>
    <li>direct sunlight or heat exposure</li>
    <li>poor airflow</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This matters because cardboard boxes, fabric bags and open tubs may not suit damp or
    dusty garages. Clear plastic tubs with lids may suit some items better, but they still
    need to be used carefully so moisture is not trapped inside.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing sensitive items directly on the floor if the garage is prone to water
    entry. Keep valuable, delicate or moisture-sensitive items inside the home where
    possible.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan for awkward items first</h2>
  <p>
    Awkward items cause more garage storage problems than small boxes.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying general shelving, identify large or difficult items such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>bikes</li>
    <li>scooters</li>
    <li>ladders</li>
    <li>prams</li>
    <li>folded chairs</li>
    <li>golf clubs</li>
    <li>surfboards</li>
    <li>fishing rods</li>
    <li>garden tools</li>
    <li>long-handled brooms and mops</li>
    <li>camping chairs</li>
    <li>sports bags</li>
    <li>tool cases</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These items often need dedicated storage. If you ignore them, they may end up leaning
    against shelves, blocking doors or falling over.
  </p>
  <p>
    For long items, check height and wall length. For bikes, check lift height, handlebar
    width, wheel size and whether the storage method is realistic for the person using it.
    For ladders, check length, weight and safe access before considering hanging storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep hazardous items out of easy reach</h2>
  <p>
    Garages often hold products that should not be casually accessible.
  </p>
  <p>These may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cleaning chemicals</li>
    <li>pesticides</li>
    <li>fuels</li>
    <li>oils</li>
    <li>batteries</li>
    <li>sharp tools</li>
    <li>power tools</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>adhesives</li>
    <li>paints</li>
    <li>solvents</li>
    <li>pool chemicals</li>
    <li>car products</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Storage for these items needs more care than ordinary household containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check product labels and manufacturer storage instructions. Keep incompatible products
    separated where required. Store hazardous items away from children and pets. Avoid
    placing chemicals above head height or anywhere they could spill onto other stored
    items.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you are unsure how something should be stored, follow the product label or seek
    appropriate advice rather than relying on a general garage storage guide.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider rental and body corporate limits</h2>
  <p>
    If you rent, live in a townhouse, unit or body corporate property, check what changes
    are allowed before buying permanent storage.
  </p>
  <p>You may need approval before:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>drilling into walls</li>
    <li>fixing rails or hooks</li>
    <li>attaching cabinets</li>
    <li>installing ceiling storage</li>
    <li>altering shared walls</li>
    <li>changing garage fixtures</li>
    <li>adding permanent shelving</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Renter-friendly garage storage usually means freestanding shelves, labelled tubs,
    portable racks, removable storage where suitable, and storage that does not damage
    surfaces.
  </p>
  <p>
    Even if a product is described as removable, check whether it suits the surface and
    whether it may leave marks or damage.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide between shelves, tubs, cabinets and wall storage</h2>
  <p>
    Different garage storage types solve different problems.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Storage type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Freestanding shelves</td>
        <td>tubs, boxes, bulk household items</td>
        <td>depth, height, load rating, floor level</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Storage tubs</td>
        <td>grouped items, seasonal gear, dust protection</td>
        <td>lid fit, stackability, label space, moisture risk</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Cabinets</td>
        <td>tools, chemicals, items needing doors</td>
        <td>depth, weight, locking, ventilation, access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Pegboards</td>
        <td>hand tools and small workshop items</td>
        <td>wall type, fixing method, tool weight</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Wall hooks/rails</td>
        <td>bikes, garden tools, sports gear</td>
        <td>wall type, load rating, installation requirements</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Workbench storage</td>
        <td>projects, tools, hardware</td>
        <td>bench height, floor space, lighting, power access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Overhead storage</td>
        <td>light, rarely used items</td>
        <td>ceiling suitability, clearance, safe lifting</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The best garage storage often combines a few types rather than relying on one system for
    everything.
  </p>

  <h2>Common garage storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Avoid these common problems before spending money:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying shelves before sorting what is being stored</li>
    <li>choosing shelves that are too deep for a garage used for parking</li>
    <li>stacking heavy tubs too high</li>
    <li>using cardboard boxes in damp or pest-prone areas</li>
    <li>buying wall hooks without checking wall type</li>
    <li>hanging bikes or ladders where they are awkward to lift</li>
    <li>storing chemicals above shoulder height</li>
    <li>blocking access to doors, meters, taps or switches</li>
    <li>storing frequently used items behind rarely used items</li>
    <li>assuming all garages are suitable for ceiling storage</li>
    <li>ignoring garage door clearance</li>
    <li>buying matching tubs that do not fit the shelf depth</li>
    <li>creating storage that makes the garage harder to use day to day</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A tidy garage is not useful if it becomes harder or less safe to access the things you
    actually need.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple garage measuring checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying garage storage, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>garage width and depth</li>
    <li>wall lengths available for storage</li>
    <li>ceiling height</li>
    <li>garage door clearance</li>
    <li>car position and door-opening clearance</li>
    <li>walking paths</li>
    <li>shelf depth that will still allow access</li>
    <li>maximum shelf height you can use safely</li>
    <li>floor slopes, drains or uneven areas</li>
    <li>power point, tap, meter and switch locations</li>
    <li>wall type</li>
    <li>moisture or pest-prone areas</li>
    <li>items that are heavy, hazardous or awkward</li>
    <li>items used weekly</li>
    <li>items used seasonally</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these measurements with you when comparing storage options. This reduces the chance
    of buying shelves, tubs or hooks that technically fit but do not work in the real
    garage.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Garage storage should start with sorting and measuring, not buying.
  </p>
  <p>For most households, the practical starting point is usually:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>remove what does not need to be stored</li>
    <li>group what remains by use and risk</li>
    <li>keep heavy and hazardous items low and controlled</li>
    <li>measure vehicle and walking clearance</li>
    <li>choose freestanding or low-risk storage first</li>
    <li>treat wall and ceiling storage cautiously</li>
    <li>only buy hooks, rails or racks after checking wall type, load ratings and installation requirements</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    A good garage storage setup should make the garage easier to use, not just fuller.
  </p>
  <p>
    If storage blocks access, creates lifting problems, hides hazardous items, traps
    moisture or depends on questionable fixings, it is not a good solution no matter how
    organised it looks.
  </p>

